review_blob: I love hops, so I love this brew. More flavor than most barleywines, the hop level may overwhelm you more than the alcohol does.
Solid stout, but the aftertaste is horrendous.
IMO not as good as the regular imperial from Sam Smith. More bready tasting.
Fruitier tasting than the red and blue varieties. Generally a more interesting drink.
More discernible flavors than I can write about. Its a carnival in your mouth. Dont give this stuff to an average beer drinker without warning, you will scare them.
Excelletn stout. Blacker than black (look at that picture on the left and realize it comes in a clear bottle). Fun earthy aftertaste.
The worst of the excellent Unibroue family. Not as in-your-face as La Fin Du Monde.
Very much like motor oil. This was apparently Kochs first attempt at high alkie creations. Inferior to the SA Millennium, which is also a curiosity but actally tastes good.
I imagine carbonated paint thinner would approximate this brew.
Excellent alcohol delivery device. The same way McDonalds fries are an excellent ketchup delivery device.
Tastes very unrefined. Has a lot of flavor--very nasty flavor.

Straight from the tap at the brewery this tasted like water. The further it gets away from that brewery, the worse it gets. When in cans may be part of a government conspiracy to reduce beer consumption. And whats with the rice, anyway?
Better than Urquell. Still hard to find in the US.
Champ of what, exactly? Bastard child of Bud and wheat beer.
Crap.
Very solid wheat beer. Might have the most perfect yeast level of any beer Ive ever had.
Excelleny chewy beer. More smoky tasting than most Dunkels.

Horrendous monstrosity of a beer. If youve ever wondered why they dont make light wheat beer, now you know. Very weak flavor with nasty aftertaste. Apologies to my German friend for lugging this to me only to watch me convulse.
Probably my least favorite Erdinger. Not even as good as Becks Oktoberfest. Seems like they engineered one of their other beers weaker to make this one.
Overpriced Coors Light with additional hops. Save money; get a Heineken and dilute with water.
Ouch. They should sell this stuff in singles. At least they realized the potency of this brew and sell it in smaller bottles. This is my cold day beer. Not as bitter or oversweet as most barleywines.
Ten bucks a 6 isnt cheap but this one is worth it. Various spicy flavors. Very very heavy, syrupy texture.
beer_name: Anchor Our Special Ale (2001 and earlier)

review_blob: Woo! More like a weak brandy than a beer. Flavor is almost candylike--erm--if they made beer candy that is. Worth trying at least once for most people, so good luck finding it.
Comes in a pretty box. Strangely fruity tasting and smells wonderful.
NOT. HOPPY. ENOUGH. This weak pretender to the IPA throne would have never made the trip from England to India.
I would have rated this much higher if it werent called ESB. It is not special, and not all that bitter.
Ill be honest, Guinness is my daily drinker. Enough said.
The coffee imparts wonderous flavors on this excellent stout. A must for stout fans and coffee fans. Be careful, as this beer does not mix well with others (in your stomach).
A solid porter. A bit weak for my tastes, and a bit too sweet.
Not as bad as your downmarket beers, but pretty bad. Like foul tasting water.

Things would be different if I were reviewing the variety of this beer which is available in Thailand. As it stands, the export version that reaches North America is a vile creation along the lines of your average malt liquor. In trying to fit into the NA market, they have left the alcohol content lower merely by reducing the fermentation time of the beer. The large amount of sugar in export Singha is very obvious, just swirl around the bottle some and you will see it coat the inside. Beer un nee yaah mak.

Tastes really good at first, but I had a real problem with this one. Aftertaste is stale and nasty. Texture of the beer is extremely syrupy. The carbonation level is much too light for a beer of this strength.

Not as good as the Blue, IMO. Nevertheless an excellent, heavy beer. If youve had any variety of Chimay before you will recognize the flavor immediately. The Red tastes more reasonable than the Blue in terms of yeast and texture.

When your lifelong Bud0swilling friends ask you what real beer tastes like, pour a wide-brimmed glass of this stuff and set it in front of them. The complexity of this stuff is utterly amazing. Unlike the other beers in the 8% and up club, Chimay seems to subliminally tell your body to slow down... a very good property, I must say.

This stuff isnt quite as nuclear as Fin (another Unibroue product) but every bit as good if not better. How they made this meaty a beer this smooth befuddles me. After your first sip you will sense the explosion of flavor sliding down your throat... very very good.

Nothing subtle about this beer. Everything about this beer is in your face, Belgian style. Be very careful, I mean it. This stuff tastes so good you wont want to stop drinking it... at this level of alcohol the beer will stop you before you decide youve had enough.

If you dont like this beer, youre missing the point. This beer is supposed to taste like half-water half-beer. Thats the way its marketed. Super dry is something you slam down after a good game of raquetball. Its refreshing like that. Notice Super Dry has just a bit less alcohol than regular Budweiser, but tastes 10,000,000% cleaner. A marvel of modern beer engineering.
Tastes like mud. Makes poor competition to Asahis vastly superior Black variety. Also carbonation seems very artificial, at your typical 7up/Sprite level.

I have a really difficult time explaining this thing. Its like the bastard child of the darkest of stouts and Bud Ice... in a good way. It has all the flavor you would ever want out of a black beer combined with the smoothness and drinkability of your average lager. Even if you dont like it, youll admit its one of the more interesting beers you have ever had.
